<paragraph id="C74C0E393E5EA1557DCDFDBCC00DFD6B" blockId="14.[189,794,489,705]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">The relevant characters are explained in more detail in the following species description. Which of them actually are diagnostic of the group depends on the possible discovery of other related species. Currently there is no similar species known in the region.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FE95DB23E5EA1557DCDFD7CC036F88B" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph id="C74C0E393E5EA1557DCDFD7CC0B0FBEB" blockId="14.[189,794,745,1825]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557DCDFD7CC30FFCAB" bold="true" box="[189,319,745,769]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Description</emphasis>
: This subgenus is characterized mainly by the terminalia of the male (
<figureCitation id="5FC812BC3E5EA1557C98FC9CC005FC8B" box="[488,565,777,801]" captionStart="Figs 22–25" captionStartId="16.[320,360,1980,2002]" captionTargetBox="[369,1274,276,1948]" captionTargetId="figure-102@16.[320,1305,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figs 22–25: Male terminalia: metasomal sterna 7 and 8 (S7, S8), genital capsule. – 22 Hylaeus (Alfkenylaeus) euphorbiae spec. nov. – 23 Hylaeus (Cornylaeus) adamauanis spec. nov. – 24 Hylaeus (Deranchylaeus) haladanius spec. nov. – 25 Hylaeus (Pumilaeus) pumilus spec. nov., S7: left ventral view, right dorsal view. – Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5370726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5370726/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). The genital capsule is oval in outline, with penis valves in the dorsal view apically broadly rounded, the apical bristles long and converging. Sternum 7 is unique: with distal lobes expanded into a pair of convex bubble-like surfaces without clear subdivision into proximal and distal parts, and without bristles. Sternum 8 is a little reminiscent of certain Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557CFEFC7CC0B5FBAB" authority="" box="[398,645,1001,1025]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Nesoprosopis">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557CFEFC7CC3D2FBAB" box="[398,482,1001,1025]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Hylaeus</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557C85FC7FC04CFBAB" box="[501,636,1002,1025]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Nesoprosopis</emphasis>
)
</taxonomicName>
species: with apical lobus prolonged, narrow, apically divided into two round lamellae with fine marginal bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C74C0E393E5EA1557DCDFBDCC036F88B" blockId="14.[189,794,745,1825]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">
According to the identification keys by 
<bibRefCitation id="A36273C83E5EA1557FC0FBDCC335FB2B" author="SNELLING, R. R." pageId="14" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref13633" refString="SNELLING, R. R. 1985: The systematics of the hylaeine bees (Hymenoptera: Colletidae) of the Ethiopian zoogeographical region: The genera and subgenera with revisions of the smaller groups. - Contributions in Science, Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County, no. 361: 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="1985">SNELLING (1985)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="A36273C83E5EA1557C64FBFCC3EBFB2B" author="MICHENER, C. D." box="[276,475,1129,1153]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" refId="ref13397" refString="MICHENER, C. D. 2007: The Bees of the World. Second Edition. The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore and London: 953 pp." type="book" year="2007">MICHENER (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="A36273C83E5EA1557F67FBFCC086FB2B" author="DATHE, H. H." box="[535,694,1129,1153]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" pagination="1 - 84" refId="ref13161" refString="DATHE, H. H. 2014: Studies on the systematics and taxonomy of the genus Hylaeus F. (8). Revision of the Afrotropic subgenus Hylaeus (Deranchylaeus) BRIDWELL (Hymenoptera: Anthophila, Colletidae). - Zootaxa 3874 (1): 1 - 84." type="journal article" year="2014">
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557F67FBFCC053FB2B" authority="Dathe, 2015" authorityName="Dathe" authorityYear="2015" box="[535,611,1129,1153]" pageId="14" pageNumber="10" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Dathe">DATHE</taxonomicName>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
, one can exclude the subgenera 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557CCBFB1CC073FB0B" authorityName="SNELLING" authorityYear="1985" box="[443,579,1161,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Alfkenylaeus">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557CCBFB1CC073FB0B" box="[443,579,1161,1185]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Alfkenylaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557F23FB1CC0FBFB0B" box="[595,715,1161,1185]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Cornylaeus</emphasis>
, 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557FABFB1FC2C3FB6B" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Metylaeus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557FABFB1FC2C3FB6B" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Metylaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557C75FB3CC34CFB6B" box="[261,380,1193,1217]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Nothylaeus</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557CCAFB3FC07AFB6B" box="[442,586,1194,1217]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Prosopisteron</emphasis>
. So far 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557FDAFB3CC12AFB6B" authority="Dathe, 2015" authorityName="Dathe" authorityYear="2015" box="[682,794,1193,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. n." subGenus="Pumilaeus">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557FDAFB3CC12AFB6B" box="[682,794,1193,1217]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Pumilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="EEB46F503E5EA1557DCDFB5CC31CFB4B" box="[189,300,1225,1249]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" rank="subGenus">subgen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
shows a number of exclusion criteria to those subgenera, but few special features of its own: (1) The sculpture of the mesosoma is regular, not coarse, with fine to moderate, dense punctation, (2) occiput and propodeum are rounded, (3) the mandibles bifid. But among the known species, 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557C88FAFCC058FA2B" authority="Dathe, 2015" authorityName="Dathe" authorityYear="2015" box="[504,616,1385,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. n." subGenus="Pumilaeus">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557C88FAFCC058FA2B" box="[504,616,1385,1409]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Pumilaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="EEB46F503E5EA1557F04FAFCC0D3FA2B" box="[628,739,1385,1409]" pageId="14" pageNumber="23" rank="subGenus">subgen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
also delimits sufficiently clearly from 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557F35FA1CC0D2FA0B" authorityName="BRIDWELL" authorityYear="1919" box="[581,738,1417,1441]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Deranchylaeus">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557F35FA1CC0D2FA0B" box="[581,738,1417,1441]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Deranchylaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: On the head, (4) the vertex is narrow and backward sloping with rounded transition; (5) the foveae faciales are extended to the vertex, where they converge strongly. The antennae are short. (6) The supraclypeal area is very flat and only faintly raised above the curvature of the face in lateral view, its lateral edges are without sharp ridges; above it merges relatively broadly into the vertex, wherein the females have in addition to the median furrow four to five striking parallel grooves on each side. Finally, (7) the very short, rounded pronotum, not expanded forward, distinguishes this taxon from the known 
<taxonomicName id="00F375BA3E5EA1557C7FF89CC39CF88B" authorityName="BRIDWELL" authorityYear="1919" box="[271,428,1801,1825]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Hylaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Deranchylaeus">
<emphasis id="F587D22B3E5EA1557C7FF89CC39CF88B" box="[271,428,1801,1825]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="23">Deranchylaeus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species.
</paragraph>
